 for bestpractices and # Session Persistence & Export

## Overview
Build a robust Session Persistence & Export system for ConverseForms that:
- Persistes every chat session transcript along with structured fields, metadata, timestamps, and attachments.
- Supports CSV and JSON exports, including streaming for large datasets, and supports scheduled exports or bulk downloads.
- Stores uploaded assets (avatars, PDFs, transcripts, attachments) in AWS S3 with pre-signed URLs and secure access.
- Provides admin-facing pages for Settings & Preferences, a Session Viewer for detailed per-session analysis, and a Dashboard for high-level metrics, recent sessions, quick actions, and system alerts.
- Enforces org-level data retention policies, data purging, and webhook integrations for real-time exports/notifications.

This prompt is tailored for an AI development tool to generate a complete, production-ready implementation with strong runtime safety, scalability, and a cohesive UX aligned to the project’s visual system.

---

## Components to Build

1) Session Persistence & Export Service (Backend)
- Purpose: Store raw transcripts, structured fields, timestamps, respondent metadata, and attachments. Provide export streaming APIs and scheduled export capabilities.
- Data model considerations:
  - Normalized session schema with: session_id, agent_id, org_id, started_at, ended_at, duration, messages (with role, content, timestamp, metadata), structured_fields (JSON), respondent_metadata (JSON), attachments (list of asset references), export_status, retention_policy_id, webhook_settings, and audit fields (created_by, updated_by, version).
  - Attachments stored as references to S3 keys; download URLs generated on demand via pre-signed URLs.
- API surface:
  - Create/Append messages to a session.
  - Get session by id (with optional embedded transcripts and structured fields).
  - List sessions with pagination and filtering (org_id, agent_id, date range, status).
  - Export: GET /api/sessions/:id/export (generate CSV/JSON or stream); POST /api/sessions/export to start a bulk export job.
  - Export streaming: support chunked responses or signed download links; support CSV and JSON formats.
  - Schedule export: API to create/export jobs with cron-like scheduling; webhook on completion.
  - Retention purge: API to purge data per org or by policy; support soft-delete and hard purge.
  - Webhooks: push export events (start, progress, complete, failed) to configured webhook URLs.
- AWS S3 integration:
  - Upload assets with pre-signed POST/PUT URLs; store assets in an organized bucket structure (org-id / agent-id / assets / [filename]).
  - Generate pre-signed URLs for download (avatar, PDFs, transcripts attachments).
- Security:
  - Validate org- and agent-owned access; enforce RBAC for export and purge actions.
  - Use least-privilege IAM roles for S3 operations; sign URLs with expiry.
- Performance/Scalability:
  - Use streaming/export jobs for large datasets; consider chunking by date ranges.
  - Implement idempotency for export requests; deduplicate exports.

2) Settings & Preferences Page (Frontend + API)
- Purpose: Account-level settings including email preferences, webhooks, LLM model defaults, storage quotas, team settings, and data retention policy.
- Data model considerations:
  - org_settings: email_notifications, webhook_endpoints (array), default_llm_model, storage_quota, data_retention_policy_id, team_settings (roles/permissions), audit logs_enabled, export_preferences (format, frequency).
- UI components:
  - Settings tabs/sections: General, Webhooks, LLM Defaults, Storage & Retention, Team & Roles, Data Export.
  - Webhook management: add/edit/remove endpoints; test ping; per-event subscriptions.
  - Retention policy selector: pre-defined policies (30/90/180 days) with custom policy option; show estimated storage impact.
  - Save/Apply with optimistic UI and proper error handling; show validation errors inline.
- API surface:
  - GET /api/org/:orgId/settings
  - PATCH /api/org/:orgId/settings
  - POST /api/org/:orgId/webhooks
  - POST /api/org/:orgId/export-policies (define custom policy)
  - POST /api/org/:orgId retention/apply
- Security:
  - Ensure org-scoped access tokens; validate ownership.
  - Rate-limiting on webhook tests; verify HMAC signatures if used.
- UX considerations:
  - Clear, contextual help text; inline validation; success toasts on save.
  - Preview of export format (sample CSV/JSON header).

3) Session Viewer Page (Frontend)
- Purpose: Detailed view of a completed or in-progress session: full transcript, extracted structured fields, collection timestamps, respondent metadata, and actions.
- UI components:
  - Session header: session_id, agent name, org, status, duration, started_at/ended_at.
  - Transcript renderer: chronological list of messages with timestamp, speaker, and content; support collapsible long messages; preserve formatting.
  - Structured fields panel: key-value grid for extracted fields; allow inline editing for annotations (optional) with audit trail.
  - Respondent metadata: device, location, IP (redact sensitive fields), consent status.
  - Attachments/Assets panel: list of assets with previews (avatar, PDFs, transcripts), download/view actions, and pre-signed URL generation.
  - Actions bar: Export (CSV/JSON), Resend to Webhook, Tag, Annotate, Purge (per-session retention exception), Add Note.
  - History & timestamps: collection timestamps, edits, and versioning.
- Runtime safety & data loading:
  - Guard all array accesses with (data ?? []) or Array.isArray checks; use default states: useState<SessionTranscript[]>([]) and similar.
- API surface:
  - GET /api/sessions/:id
  - GET /api/sessions/:id/export (CSV/JSON; supports format parameter)
  - POST /api/sessions/:id/tag
  - POST /api/sessions/:id/annotate
  - POST /api/sessions/:id/resend-webhook
  - POST /api/sessions/:id/purge (per-session)
- UX details:
  - Keyboard accessible actions; accessible color states; loading skeletons for long transcripts.
  - Real-time or near-real-time updates when a session is in-progress (optional via polling or WebSocket if available).

4) Dashboard Page (Frontend)
- Purpose: Primary workspace showing summary metrics (agents, sessions, leads), recent sessions, quick actions, and system alerts.
- UI components:
  - KPIs: total agents, total sessions, leads, retention rate, export queue length.
  - Quick actions: Create Agent, View Analytics, Schedule Export.
  - Recent Sessions: list with status icons, agent name, last message snippet, timestamps; supports click to open Session Viewer.
  - System Alerts: banner/cards showing retention policy events, storage quotas, export job failures, webhook status.
  - Analytics widgets: mini-charts for sessions/day, average session length, completion rate; filters by date range, org, agent.
  - Navigation: consistent left rail with icons; top bar for global actions; responsive behavior for mobile.
- Data loading:
  - Guard data rendering with Array.isArray and default empty states; e.g., const sessions = (data?.sessions ?? []) as SessionSummary[];
- API surface:
  - GET /api/dashboard/summary
  - GET /api/dashboard/recent-sessions
  - GET /api/dashboard/alerts
- Performance:
  - Prefetch essential data; implement debounced search/filter; caching on client where appropriate.

5) AWS S3 (Object Storage) Integration
- Purpose: Centralized asset storage for avatars, PDFs, transcripts, and attachments.
- Implementation details:
  - Bucket structure: s3://converseforms-orgs/{orgId}/{type}/{resourceId}/{filename}
  - Types: avatars, assets, transcripts, attachments, PDFs, images.
  - Pre-signed URL workflow:
    - Frontend requests a pre-signed POST/PUT URL for uploads; store resulting S3 key in DB with metadata.
    - Frontend requests a pre-signed GET URL for downloads or previews; add expiry time.
  - Asset lifecycle: lifecycle policies for old/large files; optional S3 Object Lock or versioning.
- API surface:
  - POST /api/s3/presigned-upload (orgId, type, filename, contentType) -> { url, fields, key }
  - GET /api/s3/presigned-download (key, expiry) -> { url }
  - DELETE /api/s3/asset (key) to purge assets when retention policy removes data.
- Security:
  - Use IAM roles with least privilege; sign URLs with short expiry (e.g., 15-60 minutes).
  - Validate ownership via orgId in requests; ensure only authorized services/users can request signed URLs.

6) Connected Pages
- page_006: Session Viewer (detailed per-session)
- page_011: Settings & Preferences (org-level)
- page_012: Dashboard (workspace metrics)

---

## Implementation Requirements

### Frontend
- Tech stack compatibility: React (with hooks), TypeScript, a state management approach (React context or Redux) as appropriate.
- Runtime safety:
  - All array operations guarded: (items ?? []).map(...), Array.isArray(items) ? items.map(...) : [].
  - Initialize useState with typed arrays: useState<Session[] | []>([]) or useState<YourType[]>([]).
  - API response handling: const list = Array.isArray(response?.data?.items) ? response.data.items : [].
- Components to create:
  - SessionListCard: compact card for each session in dashboard/recent lists.
  - TranscriptViewer: render transcript with collapsible sections, search, and highlight structured fields.
  - StructuredFieldsPanel: display and edit structured fields with versioning.
  - AttachmentsGallery: previews with download/pre-signed URL integration.
  - SettingsPanel: form sections for webhooks, retention, export preferences, and model defaults.
  - ExportModal: choose format (CSV/JSON), include fields, and confirm.
  - WebhookTester: UI to validate webhook endpoints.
  - S3PreSignedUploader: reusable hook/component to request pre-signed URLs and upload assets.
  - DashboardWidgets: KPI tiles, recent sessions table, alerts banner, and action panels.
- Data handling patterns:
  - All data reads from API should be guarded with null checks.
  - Normalize data into internal types, with fallback defaults.
  - Use suspense/loading placeholders where appropriate.
- Accessibility:
  - All interactive elements are keyboard accessible; ARIA labels for dynamic content.
  - Color contrast meeting WCAG AA guidelines.

### Backend
- Language/runtime: Node.js (NestJS/Express) or equivalent with TypeScript where possible; or Python (FastAPI) depending on project norms.
- Database:
  - Relational database (PostgreSQL) with normalized tables:
    - orgs (id, name, retention_policies_id, settings...),
    - agents (id, org_id, name, persona, avatar_url, etc.),
    - sessions (id, org_id, agent_id, started_at, ended_at, duration, status, respondent_meta, retention_policy_id, etc.),
    - messages (id, session_id, role, content, timestamp, metadata),
    - structured_fields (id, session_id, jsonb),
    - attachments (id, session_id, s3_key, url, type, size, uploaded_at),
    - exports (id, org_id, format, status, created_at, completed_at, file_url or s3_key, progress),
    - retention_policies (id, name, ttl_days, purge_on_expiry, description),
    - webhooks (id, org_id, url, event, auth_secret, enabled),
    - audit_logs (id, session_id, action, timestamp, user_id).
  - Ensure null-safe access and defaults for all query results.
- API endpoints (aligned with Frontend needs):
  - GET /api/sessions
  - GET /api/sessions/:id
  - GET /api/sessions/:id/export
  - POST /api/sessions/:id/tag
  - POST /api/sessions/:id/annotate
  - POST /api/sessions/:id/resend-webhook
  - POST /api/sessions/export (bulk)
  - POST /api/org/:orgId/webhooks
  - GET /api/dashboard/summary
  - GET /api/dashboard/recent-sessions
  - GET /api/dashboard/alerts
  - GET /api/s3/presigned-upload
  - GET /api/s3/presigned-download
- Export service:
  - CSV export: streaming / chunked writes to response or to a temporary storage with a downloadable URL; ensure field escaping, proper newline handling, and encoding (UTF-8).
  - JSON export: streaming NDJSON or standard JSON array; support large payloads via streaming.
  - Progress events: progress tracking, optionally a pub/sub mechanism to notify frontend via WebSocket or long-poll.
- Export scheduling:
  - Job scheduler (e.g., CRON-based or time-based) to trigger exports; store job state; allow cancellation.
- Retention & purge:
  - Automated purge per retention policy; cascade delete or soft-delete with audit; ensure no orphaned references.
- Security:
  - JWT-based authentication; org-scoped authorization; route guards; audit of data export activities.
  - Validate external webhook signatures if provided.
- File storage integration:
  - When attachments are uploaded, store S3 keys and retrieval URLs; purge on policy purge if configured.

### Integration
- Data flow:
  - When a session is created/updated, persist transcript messages and structured fields; attach any uploaded assets to the session; update respondent metadata.
  - On export request, gather sessions per policy/filters, stream as CSV/JSON, and notify user upon completion via in-app notification and/or webhook.
  - For assets (avatars, PDFs, transcripts), leverage S3 pre-signed URLs for secure upload/download; store references in DB.
  - Settings & Preferences flows update org-level configurations; session exports adhere to retention policies.
- Frontend-Backend contracts:
  - Consistent response shapes with data normalization.
  - Use robust error handling; propagate meaningful error messages to UI.
  - Use debounced/queued operations for bulk actions (exports, purges) to prevent race conditions.

---

## User Experience Flow

1) User signs in and lands on Dashboard
- Sees summarized metrics: agents, sessions, leads, recent sessions, and system alerts.
- Can click “Create Agent” or “View Analytics” for deeper actions.
- Option to schedule exports or initiate quick export of recent data.

2) User configures Settings & Preferences
- User navigates to Settings -> Webhooks, Retention, LLM Defaults, and Team Settings.
- User adds/edits webhooks, selects default LLM model, adjusts storage quotas, and sets a data retention policy.
- User saves changes; UI validates inputs; backend applies and shows a success toast.

3) User views a Session in Session Viewer
- User opens a completed or in-progress session.
- UI shows full transcript with timestamps, messages by agent/user, and a separate panel with extracted structured fields.
- Attachments are displayed with previews and options to download via pre-signed URLs.
- Actions available: Export (CSV/JSON), Resend to Webhook, Tag, Annotate, and Purge (with retention override if allowed).

4) User exports data
- User navigates to Export flow (single session or bulk).
- User selects export format (CSV or JSON), fields to include, and delivery method (download or email/push to webhook).
- Backend streams/export job; UI shows progress, and on completion provides a download link or notifies via webhook.

5) Asset upload workflow
- User uploads avatars or PDFs via pre-signed URLs.
- Frontend requests a pre-signed URL from backend, uploads directly to S3, and stores the asset reference in the session or asset table.
- Asset retrieval uses signed URLs with short expiry.

6) Data retention & purge
- Admin configures retention policy; system automatically purges eligible data according to policy or on-demand purge per org/session.
- UI indicates purge status and confirms irreversible actions.

